a. Keyboard and Mouse Activities
These are "Actions"—the bot proactively does something.
i. Mouse (Click, Double Click, Hover)
Click: Drag the Click activity. Click "Indicate on screen" and select a button.
Practical Tip: In Properties, you can change the ClickType to CLICK_SINGLE.
Double Click: Drag the Double Click activity. It works exactly like the Click activity but triggers a double-click (useful for opening desktop icons).
Hover: Drag the Hover activity. This moves the mouse over an element without clicking it.

Use Case: Use this to trigger "hover-over" menus on websites.

ii. Type Into
Drag Activity: Search for Type Into.
Indicate: Select a text field (like a Search bar).
Input Text: Type your text in double quotes: "Hello UiPath".

Special Keys: You can add keys like Enter by selecting them from the "Plus" (+) menu in the activity.

iii. Type Secure Text
Purpose: Used for typing passwords so they aren't visible in the code.
Steps:
First, you must have a SecureString variable (usually retrieved from a "Get Password" activity).
Drag Type Secure Text.
In the SecureText property, enter your SecureString variable.

b. Triggering Events
These are "Listeners"—the bot waits for something to happen before it starts an action.
i. Element Triggering Event
Use the Monitor Events activity container.
Inside it, drag an On Element Appear trigger.
Indicate: Select a pop-up window or a specific button.
Action: In the Event Handler block, put a Message Box. The bot will now sit and wait until that element shows up before showing the message.

ii. Image Triggering Event
Inside Monitor Events, drag On Image Appear.
Indicate: Draw a box around a specific logo or icon on the screen.
Result: The bot will monitor the screen and trigger the action only when that specific image is visible.

iii. System Triggering Event
Inside Monitor Events, drag a System Trigger.
Configure: In Properties, choose the Type. Options include things like "Low Battery" or "Power Connected."
Action: The bot executes the workflow when that specific system state changes.

c. Launch Assistant Bot on Keyboard Event
This is a classic "HotKey" trigger. This bot "sleeps" until you press a specific key combination.
Open a New Sequence: Name it HotKeyTrigger.
Add Activity: Search for Monitor Events and drag it in.
Add Trigger: Drag the Hotkey Trigger inside the "Triggers" section.

Configure Keys:
In the Properties, set Key to "s" (or any letter).
Check the box for Alt or Ctrl.
Result: The bot is now listening for Alt + S.
Set the Action: Inside the Event Handler section of the Monitor Events, drag the activities you want your "Assistant" to do (e.g., Open a specific website or Excel file).
Run: When you run this, the bot will stay in "Running" mode. As soon as you press Alt + S, the Assistant bot will execute.
